{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538574","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538574"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:29:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:29:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16253"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16253","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16253"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.02,0.65,0.09,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8944"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64513"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8944"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16253"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49945"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2112"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"3902"},{"type":"tags","id":"4101"},{"type":"tags","id":"4104"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"9330"},{"type":"tags","id":"9331"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21284"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43622"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64513"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of intermittent lower abdominal pain and bloating. She has regular menstrual cycles. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has two children born by normal vaginal delivery. There is no family history of ovarian or breast cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals a tender mass in the left iliac fossa. Bimanual examination confirms a left adnexal mass approximately 8 cm in diameter.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Computed tomography scan of the abdomen and pelvis","Magnetic resonance imaging of the pelvis","Transvaginal ultrasound","Cancer antigen 125 level","Transabdominal ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of an ovarian mass requiring characterisation. \u003Cstrong\u003ETransvaginal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard first-line imaging modality as it provides superior resolution and detailed assessment of pelvic masses. It can identify concerning features such as thick septations, solid components, papillary projections, and increased vascularity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransabdominal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E has lower resolution and provides less detailed characterisation of pelvic masses compared to transvaginal ultrasound, particularly for internal architecture and vascularity assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography scan\u003C/strong\u003E exposes the patient to unnecessary radiation and is generally reserved for cases where ultrasound suggests features concerning for malignancy, or for staging if malignancy is confirmed. It provides less detailed information about the internal architecture of ovarian masses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging\u003C/strong\u003E provides excellent soft tissue detail but is typically reserved for problem-solving when ultrasound findings are equivocal or when specific tissue characterisation is needed. It is not necessary as an initial investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003ECancer antigen 125\u003C/strong\u003E level may be helpful in the overall assessment, it should not delay appropriate imaging. CA-125 can be elevated in many benign conditions and has low specificity in premenopausal women.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter transvaginal ultrasound, findings can be combined with other clinical features and tumour markers to calculate the Risk of Malignancy Index (RMI), which helps determine the need for specialist referral. Simple cysts in premenopausal women can often be managed conservatively with surveillance, while complex masses may require surgical evaluation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Transvaginal ultrasound is the gold standard first-line imaging modality for evaluating pelvic masses.","Features concerning for ovarian malignancy include thick septations, solid components, papillary projections, and increased vascularity.","Risk of Malignancy Index calculation helps guide the need for specialist referral in women with ovarian masses."],"references":["Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Management of suspected ovarian masses in premenopausal women (Green-top Guideline No. 62) [Internet]. London: RCOG; 2011 [cited 2024 Nov 23]. Available from: https://www.rcog.org.uk/guidance/browse-all-guidance/green-top-guidelines/ovarian-masses-in-premenopausal-women-management-of-suspected-green-top-guideline-no-62/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49945"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16253"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49945","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49945"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T18:54:37+10:30","updatedAt":"20